We lost another giant in our industry. Lee Lorenz was an extraordinary cartoonist and also TNY’s Cartoon Editor who initiated the era of cartoonists writing their own cartoons (as opposed to using a gag writer). 
His beautiful, thick brushwork was a marvel to look at. 
Personally, he was very encouraging of my work at the magazine for which I will always be grateful.

Yesterday marked 10 years since the Boston marathon bombing. One of the most difficult cartoons I created in my career was one I drew for the @newyorkermag covering the terrible tragedy that day. Later in the day, @abcnews closed their coverage with the cartoon. 
Boston is a city I love. I remember how much it meant to me to see the outpouring of kindness and support we all shared on that day. That kind of unity seems scarce during these days of red/blue state divisions. 
It was not that long ago when we were connected and united as Americans. I’m hopeful that it won’t be too long before we feel that way again.
Good luck, @bostonmarathon! #bostonstrong

From cartoonist @christopherweyant: A king’s ransom

We lost one of our most brilliant cartoonists today, the great Sam Gross.

Sam was my friend and mentor throughout my career as he was for so many other cartoonists.
His unparalleled work at National Lampoon made me want to be a cartoonist when I was a kid. Later, when I became a cartoonist, his work in the New Yorker inspired me to be the best that I could be.
Sam was hilarious, prolific, irascible & generous. There was no one like him.
When it came to humor, no topic was too sacred or taboo for Sam - Popes, Nazis, religion, untouchable subjects - everything is on the table. 
If you don’t know his work, just Google Sam Gross and have a few belly laughs.

Thanks, Sam.

#samgross #cartoons

My eldest daughter was 3 years old when I drew her in this cartoon. 
Today, I dropped her off at college.
I can’t quite grasp how that journey could be so fast & so slow at the same time. 
But here we are. I’m so proud of who that little girl grew up to be & excited to watch her begin an amazing new journey of her own. 
Meanwhile, I think I’ll need to draw some more cartoons…

Years ago, I used to work @cfr_org. One day,  I was in a small, 4 person elevator about to go up to my office when someone opened the door to join the ride. In walked the legendary Henry Kissinger. I froze and said nothing as we ascended side by side. 
Leaving, Kissinger turned to me and said in his trademark Germanic baritone, “Goot bye.”
Looking back on his career, I wonder if his last elevator was going up or down?
